<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the SINGLE `sys_ws_definition`
    row that defines the **Case Status Lookup** Scripted REST API of the
    scoped application `x_[scope]`.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.1.1 / Section 0.4.3 / Section 0.4.4 / Section 0.5.1
    / Section 0.7.4):
      This Scripted REST API definition is the ServiceNow target replacement
      for ArkCase's anonymous case-status-lookup capability. ArkCase exposes
      this capability through a Spring service interface
        com.armedia.acm.plugins.casefile.service.GetCaseByNumberService
          - line 38: CaseFile getCaseByNumber(String caseNumber);
      with an implementation
        com.armedia.acm.plugins.casefile.service.GetCaseByNumberServiceImpl
          - line 47: public CaseFile getCaseByNumber(String caseNumber) {
                       return getCaseFileDao().findByCaseNumber(caseNumber);
                     }
      that delegates to a JPA DAO. ArkCase's portal gateway
      (acm-services/acm-service-portal-gateway/.../PortalRequestService.java
       line 71-72: PortalResponse getRequestStatus(String portalId,
                   String portalUserId, String requestType, String requestId)
                   throws PortalRequestServiceException;)
      wraps this lookup behind a pluggable Spring-bean indirection that
      resolves a request-type-specific provider (e.g., FOIA).

      The ServiceNow target eliminates the Spring-bean indirection entirely:
        - This `sys_ws_definition` record provides the URL-routing surface
          (the API namespace and base URL) of the lookup endpoint.
        - The paired `sys_ws_operation` record
          (../portal/rest/sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup_get.xml)
          provides the actual GET handler script.
        - The handler script delegates to the
          `x_[scope].CasePortalService.lookupCase()` Script Include method
          (../script_includes/x_[scope]_CasePortalService.xml) which performs
          the GlideRecord query and the field-whitelist enforcement.

      The result-shape contract (AAP Section 0.4.4 verbatim):
        "a result panel that shows status, subject, opened_date when found,
         or the literal text 'No case found with that number.' when not
         found. No internal fields (assigned_group, assigned_agent,
         description, closed_date, requester_*) are exposed."
      is implemented in the Script Include (the field whitelist) and the
      operation script (the verbatim 404 text). THIS file is purely metadata
      (the URL container and authentication policy); it has no scripts.

    THE DEFINITION RECORD IS THE API "CONTAINER", THE OPERATION IS THE
    HANDLER:
      ServiceNow's Scripted REST API data model splits each endpoint into
      two records:

        1. `sys_ws_definition` (THIS RECORD) - the API "namespace" container.
           Declares the URL prefix (`/api/<namespace>/<api_id>`) and the
           authentication policy (anonymous-allowed). The definition record
           contains NO handler scripts. The relationship is 1-to-N: a
           single definition can host multiple HTTP-method handlers via
           multiple operation records.

        2. `sys_ws_operation` (sibling record under
           `../rest/sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup_get.xml`)
           - the actual HTTP-method handler. Declares the HTTP method
           (GET), the relative path within the API namespace, the
           consumed/produced content types (application/json), and the
           inline operation script that returns the response body.

      For Case Status Lookup, the definition has exactly ONE operation
      (GET); the separation is required by the platform's data model
      regardless of operation count.

    URL PATH COMPOSITION (AAP Section 0.5.1 verbatim:
    "/api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup"):
      The full URL is composed by the platform from THIS record's two URL
      identifiers:

        URL = /api/<namespace>/<api_id>
            = /api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup

      where:
        - `<namespace>x_[scope]</namespace>` is the SCOPE-PREFIXED part
          (the `x_[scope]` segment). This is REQUIRED to be the scope id
          so that the URL is uniquely scoped on the PDI; multiple scoped
          apps can have endpoints with the same `api_id` value without
          collision because each app has a unique namespace. The PDI
          auto-resolves `x_[scope]` to the actual scope id (e.g.,
          `x_12345`) at App Engine Studio creation time.

        - `<api_id>case_status_lookup</api_id>` is the BARE endpoint name
          (the trailing segment). NO scope prefix here - the platform
          AUTOMATICALLY prepends `<namespace>` to the URL path. Including
          the scope prefix in `api_id` would result in the doubled URL
          `/api/x_[scope]/x_[scope]_case_status_lookup`, which is wrong.

      The lookup widget at `../widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_lookup_widget.xml`
      invokes this URL via a client-side `$http.get()` (or equivalent fetch)
      call with a `?number=<caseNumber>` query parameter. The widget URL
      composition matches THIS record's namespace + api_id.

    ANONYMOUS ACCESS (AAP Section 0.4.4 verbatim: "two unauthenticated
    pages"; AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim: "the literal text 'No case found
    with that number.' MUST appear when the lookup case number does not
    match"):
      Three configuration mechanisms work together at THIS definition record
      to permit unauthenticated callers:

        1. `<requires_authentication>false</requires_authentication>` -
           explicit signal to the platform's authentication layer that the
           API namespace itself does NOT require an authenticated session.
           This is the cornerstone of the anonymous-access design: the
           platform checks this flag FIRST when routing the request; if
           it were `true`, the platform would reject anonymous callers
           with HTTP 401 BEFORE the operation record's settings were even
           consulted.

        2. `<requires_acl_authorization>false</requires_acl_authorization>`
           - signal that the platform's ACL-evaluation layer should NOT
           run table-level ACLs against the scripted REST request. The
           privacy perimeter for anonymous lookup is the field-whitelist
           in the Script Include's return value (status, subject,
           opened_date only) - not table-level ACLs. If table-level ACLs
           ran here, anonymous callers (who have no roles) would be
           denied with HTTP 403, which would defeat the public-portal
           use case.

        3. `<requires_snc_internal_role>false</requires_snc_internal_role>`
           - signal that the platform should NOT require the OOB
           `snc_internal` role. The `snc_internal` role gates platform-
           internal APIs; setting this `false` is the ServiceNow-canonical
           way to declare an API as externally-facing.

      Plus `<enforce_acl/>` is empty - no specific table-list to enforce
      ACLs against. The privacy perimeter is the field-whitelist in the
      Script Include, NOT table-level ACLs.

      Per AAP layered-defense convention, the paired `sys_ws_operation`
      record ALSO sets `requires_authentication=false`. ServiceNow checks
      both: definition first, then operation. If either rejects anonymous
      callers, the request fails. Setting both `false` is the canonical
      anonymous-API pattern.

    DEFAULT CONTENT-TYPE CASCADE (`<consumes/>` and `<produces/>` empty):
      ServiceNow's Scripted REST API model uses cascading defaults: empty
      values at the definition level mean "use whatever the operation
      specifies." The operation record at
      `../portal/rest/sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup_get.xml`
      specifies `<consumes>application/json</consumes>` and
      `<produces>application/json</produces>` - those values cascade up.

      Per the agent prompt's Phase 4 specification:
        "<consumes/> Empty (the operation record specifies application/json)
         <consumes_customized>false</consumes_customized> Use platform default
         <produces/> Empty (the operation record specifies application/json)
         <produces_customized>false</produces_customized> Use platform default"
      this is the canonical pattern across ServiceNow scoped REST APIs.

    NO HARDCODED SYS_IDS (AAP Section 0.7.2 - non-negotiable):
      Every cross-reference in this record is by-name:
        - `<sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>`
          resolves against the scope record's `<name>x_[scope]</name>`
          (per ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml line: "<name>x_[scope]</name>").
        - `<sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>`
          resolves against the sys_app record's `<scope>x_[scope]</scope>`
          (per ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml line:
          "<scope>x_[scope]</scope>").
      The text-node value `x_[scope]` is the ACTUAL `<name>` of the scope
      record - this is the same convention applied by every sibling XML
      in this scoped application (e.g., ../portal/sp_portal_x_[scope]_case_portal.xml,
      ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml,
      ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_description.xml).

      The ONLY `sys_id` literal in this file is `<sys_id>` itself (THIS
      record's own primary key). Per AAP Section 0.7.2, the
      no-hardcoded-sys_id rule applies to references TO OTHER records,
      not to a record's own identity primary key. The `<sys_id>` value
      is the deterministic 32-char lowercase hex MD5 of the
      `<sys_update_name>`:
        printf '%s' 'sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup' | md5sum | cut -c1-32
        -> b04176032af365e6b8770ba3e6089b58
      This guarantees byte-identical re-generation on any system that has
      the standard `md5sum` utility.

    ACTIVE FLAG (AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 5 dependency):
      `<active>true</active>` - REQUIRED so the platform's request-routing
      layer accepts requests at `/api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup`. An
      inactive definition results in HTTP 404 from the routing layer,
      BEFORE the operation script even runs. That HTTP 404 would
      coincidentally match the AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim text "No case
      found with that number." but would actually be a routing failure,
      NOT a no-match - that distinction matters for diagnostics. We keep
      the definition active so that no-match HTTP 404 responses come from
      the operation script's deliberate verbatim text, not from the
      platform's routing layer.

    URL UNIQUENESS (ServiceNow platform constraint):
      `<api_id>` plus `<namespace>` together form a uniqueness constraint
      on the `sys_ws_definition` table (per-instance, the platform forbids
      two definitions sharing both fields). The scope-prefixed
      `<namespace>x_[scope]</namespace>` plus the bare
      `<api_id>case_status_lookup</api_id>` ensure global uniqueness even
      with other scoped apps on the same PDI. The literal `[scope]`
      placeholder is replaced by the actual scope id at PDI assignment
      time, so the final URL on a real instance becomes
        /api/x_<actual_scope>/case_status_lookup
      (e.g., /api/x_12345/case_status_lookup).

    NO PII, NO EMAIL (AAP Section 0.7.2 - non-negotiable):
      The description below contains ZERO PII (no real names, no real email
      addresses, no real organization names). Email notifications are
      explicitly disabled on the PDI per AAP Section 0.7.2 Email-disabled
      constraint - this REST API definition record has no email-trigger
      configuration of any kind (the definition record is purely metadata;
      the operation script - in the sibling sys_ws_operation record -
      contains no `gs.eventQueue(...)` calls either, and the Script
      Include `x_[scope].CasePortalService.lookupCase()` is a pure
      read-only lookup).

    `[scope]` PLACEHOLDER PRESERVATION (AAP Section 0.7.2 - non-negotiable):
      All `x_[scope]_*` references in `<namespace>`, `<sys_update_name>`,
      `<sys_scope>`, `<sys_package>`, and the `<description>` body
      preserve the literal `[scope]` placeholder in square brackets. The
      PDI auto-resolves to the actual scope id (e.g., `x_12345_*`) at
      App Engine Studio creation time when the Update Set is imported.
      This placeholder convention is observed consistently across every
      sibling XML in this scoped application.

    XML CONVENTIONS HONORED (matching sibling files in this app):
      - Wrapper element: `<record_update table="sys_ws_definition">` per
        the agent prompt's Phase 1 specification, matching the sibling
        pattern used by `../portal/sp_portal_x_[scope]_case_portal.xml`
        (`<record_update table="sp_portal">`) and other primary-record
        XMLs.
      - Inner element: `<sys_ws_definition action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">`.
      - Indentation: 4 spaces for record fields (matching sibling-file
        convention).
      - Element ordering: alphabetical within the record (matching
        sibling-file convention - see
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml).
      - sys_scope text-node value: `x_[scope]` (NOT
        `x_[scope]_case_management`). The actual scope record's `<name>`
        is `x_[scope]` per ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml, matching
        every sibling XML in this scoped app.
      - sys_package text-node value: `x_[scope]` with `source="x_[scope]"`
        attribute, matching the sys_app record's `<scope>x_[scope]</scope>`
        per ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml.
      - sys_class_name: literal `sys_ws_definition` (the table name).
      - sys_update_name: full scope-prefixed identifier
        `sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup` - this is the
        cross-record identifier used by the operation record's
        `<web_service_definition>` reference body to resolve the parent
        definition.
      - Deterministic 32-char lowercase hex sys_id: computed as
        MD5("sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup") =
        b04176032af365e6b8770ba3e6089b58. Re-generation of this XML is
        byte-identical (no random UUIDs).
      - Audit fields: `<sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>` and
        `<sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>` for stable
        repeatable timestamps (the same date is used by EVERY sibling
        record in this scoped app for repeatable XML re-generation).
      - No smart quotes, no leading/trailing whitespace, no BOM. Strict
        XML conformance for ServiceNow Update Set re-import preview
        (AAP Section 0.7.3 validation gate 7).

    SCHEMA-DRIVEN COMPLIANCE (assigned-file `exports` schema):
      The schema requires:
        name: x_[scope]_case_status_lookup
        kind: rest_definition
        members_exposed:
          - api_id=case_status_lookup
          - namespace=x_[scope]
          - url=/api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup
        is_default: true

      All three members are materialized:
        - `<api_id>case_status_lookup</api_id>` (line below)
          satisfies "api_id=case_status_lookup".
        - `<namespace>x_[scope]</namespace>` (line below)
          satisfies "namespace=x_[scope]".
        - The composed URL "/api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup" is the
          platform-derived value of `/api/<namespace>/<api_id>` -
          the platform exposes this URL automatically once both fields
          are set; no separate `<url>` field exists on the
          `sys_ws_definition` table.

    CROSS-DEPENDENCIES (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record; `<sys_scope>`
          cross-reference resolves against this record's `<name>`).
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped
          application record; `<sys_package>` cross-reference resolves
          against this record's `<scope>`).

      THIS RECORD MUST LOAD BEFORE:
        - sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup_get.xml (the GET
          operation references this definition via the
          `<web_service_definition>x_[scope]_case_status_lookup</web_service_definition>`
          field, which resolves against THIS record's `<sys_update_name>`).
        - ../widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_lookup_widget.xml (the
          widget calls `GET /api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup`,
          transitively dependent on this URL being registered).

      The platform's two-pass Update Set import resolves cross-references
      in any order within the same Update Set, but logically the
      definition must exist for the operation record to bind correctly.

    VALIDATION-GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3 - the seven validation
    gates):
      This definition record is the FOUNDATIONAL artifact for Validation
      Gate 5 ("Portal - lookup"):
        "Status lookup returns correct data for valid case number -
         Correct status / subject / opened_date returned; 'No case found
         with that number.' for invalid number"

      Specifically:
        - The `<requires_authentication>false</requires_authentication>`
          flag at the definition level enables anonymous access to the
          API namespace.
        - The `<api_id>` and `<namespace>` together determine the URL
          path `/api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup` that the lookup
          widget targets.
        - Without this definition record, the operation record
          (sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup_get.xml) would
          have no parent definition and the platform would not register
          the endpoint at all.

      This file is one of two foundational artifacts (this + the
      operation record) that together implement the lookup endpoint.
      Both must be present for Gate 5 to pass.

      Gates 1 (data model), 2 (workflow), 3 (ACLs), 4 (portal-submission),
      6 (dashboards), and 7 (Update Set integrity) are not affected by
      this file directly - though Gate 7 indirectly depends on this
      file's XML well-formedness and reference resolvability.

    KEY DESIGN INVARIANTS FOR FUTURE MAINTAINERS:
      1. The `<api_id>` is BARE (`case_status_lookup`) - it does NOT
         carry the scope prefix because the platform automatically
         prepends `<namespace>` to the URL path.
      2. The `<sys_update_name>` IS scope-prefixed
         (`sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup`) - it is the
         cross-record identifier used across the entire PDI's update-set
         engine, so it MUST include the scope prefix for global
         uniqueness.
      3. The `<namespace>` IS scope-prefixed (`x_[scope]`) - it is the
         URL-path segment that the platform uses for routing.
      4. The `<sys_scope>` text-node is the scope's `<name>` value
         (`x_[scope]`), NOT `x_[scope]_case_management` - this matches
         the actual scope record's `<name>` field on disk, ensuring
         Update Set re-import resolves the cross-reference cleanly.
      5. There is NO `<short_description>` field - the
         `sys_ws_definition` schema doesn't have one; we use
         `<description>` for the long-form explanation.
      6. There is NO `<security_policy>` field - the `sys_ws_definition`
         schema doesn't have one; access control is governed by
         `<requires_authentication>`, `<requires_acl_authorization>`,
         `<requires_snc_internal_role>`, `<enforce_acl>`.

    SOURCE-SIDE SEMANTIC REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
    ported per AAP Section 0.5.1):

      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
      com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/GetCaseByNumberService.java
        line 36-39 - public interface GetCaseByNumberService {
                       CaseFile getCaseByNumber(String caseNumber);
                     }

      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
      com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/GetCaseByNumberServiceImpl.java
        line 47-50 - public CaseFile getCaseByNumber(String caseNumber) {
                       return getCaseFileDao().findByCaseNumber(caseNumber);
                     }

      ArkCase implements case-status lookup as a Spring service that takes
      a case-number string and returns the full `CaseFile` JPA entity.
      The ServiceNow target re-shapes this:
        - The "URL routing" semantic maps to THIS sys_ws_definition
          record (the namespace + api_id that determine the URL path).
        - The "method binding" semantic maps to the paired sys_ws_operation
          record (the GET handler script).
        - The "lookup execution" semantic maps to the
          x_[scope].CasePortalService.lookupCase() Script Include method.
        - The "field whitelist" semantic (returning ONLY status, subject,
          opened_date - NOT the full CaseFile equivalent) is the privacy
          contract enforced in the Script Include.
      THIS file does NOT contain the lookup logic - it contains the URL
      and authentication-policy metadata that determines WHERE the
      lookup endpoint is exposed and WHO can call it (anonymous yes).
-->
<record_update table="sys_ws_definition">
    <sys_ws_definition action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <api_id>case_status_lookup</api_id>
        <consumes/>
        <consumes_customized>false</consumes_customized>
        <description>Scripted REST API definition for the Case Status Lookup endpoint. Provides anonymously-accessible GET /api/x_[scope]/case_status_lookup for the unauthenticated Experience Portal lookup widget (../widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_lookup_widget.xml). The HTTP-method handler lives in the paired sys_ws_operation record (sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup_get.xml). The handler delegates the lookup and field-whitelist enforcement to the x_[scope].CasePortalService.lookupCase() Script Include method. Returns ONLY status, subject, opened_date (no internal fields) per AAP Sections 0.4.4 and 0.7.4. Returns the verbatim text 'No case found with that number.' on no-match. Replaces ArkCase's GetCaseByNumberService anonymous-status-lookup pattern. Anonymous access is enabled by setting requires_authentication=false, requires_acl_authorization=false, and requires_snc_internal_role=false on this definition record (and on the paired operation record); the privacy perimeter is the field whitelist in the Script Include, not table-level ACLs.</description>
        <enforce_acl/>
        <name>Case Status Lookup</name>
        <namespace>x_[scope]</namespace>
        <produces/>
        <produces_customized>false</produces_customized>
        <requires_acl_authorization>false</requires_acl_authorization>
        <requires_authentication>false</requires_authentication>
        <requires_snc_internal_role>false</requires_snc_internal_role>
        <sys_class_name>sys_ws_definition</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>b04176032af365e6b8770ba3e6089b58</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>Case Status Lookup</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup</sys_update_name>
